{{Infobox Sport governing body | assocname = Rwanda Cricket Association | abbrev = (RCA) | logo = | sport = [[Cricket]] | category = | image = | caption = | jurisdiction = National | founded = | aff = [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) | affdate = | region = | regionyear = | headquarters = | location = | president = | chairman = | board = | chair = | chiefexec = | secretary = | coach = | womenscoach = | operating income = | sponsor = | year closed = | replaced = | prevfounded = | url = | countryflag = Rwanda | countryflag2 = | countryflag3 = }}
'''Rwanda Cricket Association''' is the official [[Sport governing body|governing body]] of the sport of [[cricket]] in [[Rwanda]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/cricketers-delivering-rwanda-from-hatred-christopher-shale-2r7w7gpw9|title=Cricketers delivering Rwanda from hatred|first=James|last=Gheerbrant|date=14 October 2017|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2018|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/projects/Fields-Of-Dreams/index.html|title=Field of dreams|first=Nick|last=Hoult|date=18 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2018|via=s.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Its current headquarters is located in [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]]. Rwanda Cricket Association is Rwanda's representative at the [[International Cricket Council]] and is an affiliate member and has been a member of that body since 2003. It is also a member of the [[African Cricket Association]].
==Ground==
[[Rwanda Cricket Stadium]] or [[Kicukiro Oval]] is the main cricket ground in [[Kigali]]. In August 2011, [[Rwanda Cricket Stadium Foundation]] was formed to build and manage, on a not-for-profit basis, the first dedicated international cricket ground in [[Rwanda]]. It is located on a 4.5-hectare site on the edge of Kigali, Rwanda's capital.<ref name="independent.co.uk">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/rwanda-cricket-kigali-stadium-foundation-a8033391.html|title=Welcome to Rwanda, where cricket dreams are becoming reality|date=2 November 2017|publisher=|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref>
The charity is run by a team of cricket enthusiasts from the [[UK]] [[Christopher Shale]] and Rwanda in partnership with the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] Foundation.<ref name="independent.co.uk"/> The ground was expected to be completed in 2014.
The construction of Rwanda's first dedicated cricket ground will provide a permanent home for the sport, helping its development and increasing opportunity for thousands of disadvantaged young people.
In 2012, [[Brian Lara]] agreed to become one of the patrons. The stadium is also supported by [[British Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]], [[Andrew Mitchell]], [[Jonathan Agnew]], [[Heather Knight (cricketer)|Heather Knight]], [[Peter Gummer, Baron Chadlington]]
===Facilities=== * An international-standard cricket ground (one Astroturf wicket; several grass wickets) * Pavilion (with restaurant, bar and conference facilities) * Six cricket nets * Modest spectator seating * Car parking (c. 80 spaces) * Soft (green) landscaping
