[[Image:Flag of the Seychelles.svg|thumb|100px|Flag of Seychelles]]
[[Image:SEYCGA.png|thumb|250px|The Official Logo of the Seychelles Commonwealth Games Association]]

The '''[[Seychelles]]''' was represented at the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]] in Melbourne by a 32-member strong contingent comprising 22 sportspersons and 10 officials. The 2006 event was the fifth time the nation has entered the [[Commonwealth Games]], previously having won three medals &ndash; two silver and one bronze. The Seychelles team competed in seven of the 16 sporting disciplines at the Games, including [[Athletics at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|athletics]], [[Boxing at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|boxing]], [[Weightlifting at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|weightlifting]], [[Badminton at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|badminton]], [[Table Tennis at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|table tennis]], [[Aquatics at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|swimming]] and [[Cycling at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|cycling]]. Reigning Seychelles Sportslady of the Year, [[Javelin throw|javelin]] specialist [[Lindy Leveau-Agricole]] was chosen to be the team's flag bearer during the opening ceremony.

Weightlifter Janet Thelermont became the Seychelles' first medal winner of the Games, taking a bronze in the Women's 69&nbsp;kg class after lifting 205 [[kilogram|kg]] (95&nbsp;kg [[snatch (weightlifting)|snatch]], 110&nbsp;kg [[clean and jerk]]). This result made her only the fourth Seychellois to win a Commonwealth Games medal, and the first outside of [[boxing]]. Four days later, France-based athlete [[Céline Laporte]] became the nation's second medallist, taking bronze in the [[Athletics at the 2006 Commonwealth Games#long jump women|women's long jump]] with a 6.57 metre leap, 25 centimetres further than her personal best before the Games, and was equal to that of [[Australia at the 2006 Commonwealth Games|Australian]] silver medallist [[Kerrie Taurima]].

